        <div class="ians-column">

          <p>Remember - stress in itself is not always a bad thing. Short-term stress is not only useful, it gives us the impetus to respond to problems.  When we feel stressed by something, chemical changes occur in our bodies which prepare us to deal with whatever it is that makes us stressed e.g. adrenalin rush or heightened alertness.  When the activity is over, the body returns to normal and no harm has been done; the body has adapted and we remain healthy.</p>

          <p>However, the body cannot cope so readily with the impact of continual stress over longer periods of time.  As a stressful situation continues, the body struggles to cope and damage is done.</p>

          <img class="oj-coping-graph" src="images/coping-graph-V2.svg" alt="A graph showing ability to cope reducing over time">

          <p>An effective way to alleviate stress is to <strong>identify</strong>, <strong>monitor and</strong> attempt to <strong>remove</strong> as many of the stressors as possible, for yourself and your student.</p>

          {# <p class="oj-dev-notes">I've moved the paragraph above from two paragraphs above as it seems a more logical place for it leading into the next section.</p> #}

          <h2>Stress Appraisal</h2>

          {# <p class="oj-dev-notes">3 panel</p> #}

          <p>The perception of something as a stressor contains an appraisal i.e. "What is this demand that is being placed upon me?"</p>

          <p>Immediately following this primary appraisal is a secondary appraisal. "Can I cope with the demand?"</p>

          <p>The appraisal of stressors and subsequent reaction is called the Stress Reaction.</p>

          <p>Stressors and Stress Reactions can be classified into <strong>three</strong> fundamental <strong>categories</strong> of stress, which we will now discuss.</p>

          <h2>Reactions to Stressors</h2>

          <p>It is important to remember that we all cope and react to stress in different ways, each of us have differing levels of tolerance and different methods of coping.  We also perceive the type and intensity of stress differently.</p>

