                <div class="ians-bg-blue-dark oj-list-symptoms-text oj-notched">
                  <p>Physical stressors are familiar to us all and generally get the most attention. They come in various shapes and forms, from acute chronic pain to inflammation and suffering from an illness. 43% of all adults suffer adverse health effects from stress.</p>

                  <p>The <strong>immediate</strong> physical response to a stressful situation involves overall heightened arousal of the body such as increased blood pressure, tensing of the muscles and the release of sugars and fats into circulation to provide fuel for "fight or flight".</p>

                  <p>
                    <strong>Prolonged</strong> stress and its continuous effects on the body may produce longer-term physical symptoms such as muscle tension and pain, headaches, gastrointestinal problems and decreased immunity to infectious diseases.</p>

                  <p>
                    <strong>Sleep</strong> is a big factor with adrenal fatigue. Most of us don't sleep enough or the quality of our sleep is generally poor. On top of that, we are always on the go and rarely take the rest and time out that we need.</p>
