                  <p>
                    <strong>Prolonged</strong> stress may affect thinking (a.k.a cognition).</p>

                  <p>It is important to remember that one or more of these symptoms <strong>in isolation</strong> may not necessarily point to a problem, but it could be a tell-tale sign of possible future problems.</p>

                  <p>These symptoms do not necessarily appear simultaneously and some physical symptoms may have causes other than stress. Part of the problem is that it is often the case that stress does not show itself in such an obvious way. Some forms of stress, even of a major degree, may be <strong>masked</strong> by activity.</p>

                  <p>The most common and obvious signs of stress are generally recognised as persistent tiredness, anxiety and depression, but any reactions, including those we have mentioned, can be an indication of stress, especially if they are <strong>out-of-character</strong>.</p>

