            <h2>Effects of Stress on Training</h2>

            <p>Prolonged stress may affect thinking (a.k.a. cognition) as well as emotions and behaviour. This is a serious issue for students, as problems with judgement, attention, or concentration pose a great risk to air safety.</p>

            <p>For example, under high stress conditions there is a tendency to oversimplify problem solving and ignore important relevant information, taking the "easy way out." This is called the <strong>Simplification Heuristic</strong>.</p>

            <h3>Stress-related Regression</h3>

            <p>Many individuals under high stress conditions will also <strong>forget learned procedures and skills</strong> and revert to <strong>bad habits</strong> in a phenomenon called Stress-Related Regression.</p>

            {% image "images/forgetting.jpg",
            "ATCO during OJT." %}

            <p>For example, a student controller managing a very busy arrival sequence may forget to cancel speed restrictions on some aircraft and after realising the problem, may start feeling stressed and embarrassed. He may then decide to use vectoring instead of speed control. This action would be contrary to his training and represents a kind of regression or failure to utilize prior learning.</p>

            <h3>Perceptual Tunnelling</h3>

            <p>Yet another stress-related cognitive error is Perceptual Tunnelling. It is a phenomenon in which an air traffic controller or a team under high stress becomes <strong>focused on one stimulus</strong>, such as an aircraft experiencing an unusual situation, and <strong>neglects</strong> to attend to other important <strong>tasks</strong> or <strong>information</strong>, such as other aircraft in the sector which require climb or descent clearances.</p>

            {# <p class="oj-dev-notes">Is it worth referencing this quite famous example of perception tunneling? https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JzlvgtPIof4</p> #}

            <p>Beyond affecting memory, judgement and attention, stress can even decrease hand-eye coordination and muscle control.</p>

            <p class="">Any stress that interferes with the quality of training must be considered to be relevant. Let's look at some of the consequences:</p>

