          <div class="ians-column">

            <p>There is <strong>no way we can eliminate all stress</strong> from the training process and since certain types of stress are positive and productive (Challenge) we would not want to. Stress is inherent in the process of exposure to the unknown, and as we all know, no matter how much theory or simulated practice you have had, "real life" is another world!</p>

            <p>Stress of the "threat" or of the "harm/loss" type is capable of interfering significantly with training. As we have discussed, these types of threats can occur as a result of the training process or originate from events outside training.</p>

            <p>Regardless of where it comes from, if it reaches a level that is difficult for the student to cope with, stress will have a counterproductive effect on training.</p>

            <h2>Ways to Prevent Stress in Training</h2>

            <p class="">There are <strong>three fundamental conditions</strong> that should exist for a student to feel equipped to cope with demands of OJT without unnecessary stress:</p>

          </div>

